In this posting:
[1] Santander
[2] Quindío

******
[1] Santander
Date: Wed 15 Aug 2018
Source: Vanguardia [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://rnsdaily.com/2018/08/15/seven-horseback-rides-suspended-in-santander-due-to-cases-of-equine-influenza/


Girón, Sabana de Torres, Tona, Hato, Villanueva, Guaca, and Palmas del Socorro are the 7 municipalities of Santander [department] where the horse parades will not be found among the celebrations or fairs during the next weekends.

The Secretary of Agriculture of Santander, Javier Sarmiento, told Vanguardia.com that 7 new cases of equine influenza type A, detected in Piedecuesta, Lebrija, Los Santos, Suaita, and Guadalupe, require extreme sanitary measures.

The official added that the Colombian Agricultural Institute, ICA, asked the mayors and the Governor "to cancel horse concentrations because direct contact is the main means of transmitting the disease." However, the measure will not affect equine exhibitions.

Those who fail to comply with the measure, Sarmiento clarified, "will surely be sanctioned with the Police Code. [Authorities] will be on hand to avoid mobilizations."

The official noted that the ban on horse parades will continue until the end of August [2018] "and depending on how the disease progresses we will take the appropriate measures."

The presence of influenza, in addition to affecting the fair activities, generates economic losses to the owners of the affected animals "because they must treat them and the treatments are expensive."

The Secretary of Agriculture explained that the disease is only transmitted to horses, mules, and donkeys, and does not harm the health of humans.

The symptoms that animals present include, "mucus discharge, decreased physical performance, lack of appetite, and difficulty in breathing," Sarmiento added.

[Byline: Maria Alejandra Morales]

